text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!MorphosyntacticDiversity]]%0a%0a!"only" in Indian English%0a%0a:Author: AnanyaV%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aIn Indian English, "only" is often used as a left-focus marker%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIt is often common in Indian English to use “only” as a means of adding emphasis. For example:%0a%0a# “I only cleaned the house.” (Translation: I cleaned the house myself)%0a# “My sister is like that only.” (Translation: That’s just what my sister is like)%0a%0aThis marks a deviation from standard English where “only” precedes its main referent, termed “right-focus” (e.g: “There is only one cookie left in the box”) - by contrast, “only” in Indian English is preceded by its main referent, termed “left-focus”. This left-focus use of “only” is reflected in a number of Indian languages such as Hindi, Marathi, and Tamil (for example in Tamil, the phrase “Aval appadithan” translates to ”she’s like that only”, which in standard English means ”that is just how she is” - here “than” means “only“). %0a%0aI use the Indian English morphosyntactic variant of “only” occasionally with my parents and some of my Indian friends, although I generally use it less now than I did while growing up in India due to environmental shifts. While the use of “only” in the Indian English context is not very common in public and formal dialogues in India (perhaps due to being stigmatized as “poor English”), it is quite prevalent in private and informal ones. %0a%0aSource: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/309168570_Familiarity_comprehension_and_use_of_Indian_English_only_L1_Indian_English_speakers'_psycholinguistic_judgments_and_interview_responses%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210411-205942-740180#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Personal reflection on "only" %0a-> - sanjana_m%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aWhen I was younger, I used to travel to India every few years to visit my family, and I found that I was often subconciously switching some constructs I used. One example is the way I used "only." At first, going into stores and saying things like "I only will take that one," which to me meant that I would only buy that one thing, was actually interpreted like "I am the one who is going to get that item." Once I started to realize this, I became aware of how I was using certain words, and essentially just switched the way I talked to say things like "I only cleaned the dishes", meaning that I was the one who cleaned the dishes, not my sister. Then, coming back home and using "only" like this caused some confusion with my friends, which is when I realized that that construct is mainly used in Indian English. After an older cousin explained to me that the way the word is used is different in the US and India, I knew to switch the way I talked based on my environment.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210411-205942-740180#%0a#foxbegin 210416-153255-336840#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!"itself" is used in a similar way %0a-> - Mihir_D%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0a"itself" is used very similarly to "only" in Indian English. For example, "I finished my homework today itself". In Standard English this is considered redundant. Redundant language seems to be common in casual speech, as the phrase "return back" is often used as well (instead of just "return" or "come back"). In this case, "itself" could be replaced with "only" as well to have a similar meaning. %0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210416-153255-336840#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: E:)%0a(:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)
