 is reflected in a number of Indian languages such as Hindi, Marathi, and Tamil (for example in Tamil, the phrase “Aval appadithan” translates to ”she’s like that only”, which in standard English means ”that is just how she is” - here “than” means “only“). %0a> %0a> I use the Indian English morphosyntactic variant of “only” occasionally with my parents and some of my Indian friends, although I generally use it less now than I did while growing up in India due to environmental shifts. While the use of “only” in the Indian English context is not very common in public and formal dialogues in India (perhaps due to being stigmatized as “poor English”), it is quite prevalent in private and informal ones. %0a> %0a
