diff:1618113231:1618113231:=1,76d0%0a%3c (:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c [[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a%3c [[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c [[!MorphosyntacticDiversity]]%0a%3c %0a%3c !The use of "only" in Indian English%0a%3c %0a%3c :Author: AnanyaV%0a%3c %0a%3c '''Summary:''' \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c In Indian English, "only" is often used as a left-focus marker%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c It is often common in Indian English to use “only” as a means of adding emphasis. For example:%0a%3c %0a%3c “I only cleaned the house.” (Translation: I cleaned the house myself)%0a%3c “My sister is like that only.” (Translation: That’s just what my sister is like)%0a%3c %0a%3c This marks a deviation from standard English where “only” precedes its main referent, termed “right-focus” (e.g: “There is only one cookie left in the box”) - by contrast, “only” in Indian English is preceded by its main referent, termed “left-focus”. This left-focus use of “only” is reflected in a number of Indian languages such as Hindi, Marathi, and Tamil (for example in Tamil, the phrase “Aval appadithan” translates to ”she’s like that only”, which in standard English means ”that is just how she is” - here “than” means “only“). %0a%3c %0a%3c I use the Indian English morphosyntactic variant of “only” occasionally with my parents and some of my Indian friends, although I generally use it less now than I did while growing up in India due to environmental shifts. While the use of “only” in the Indian English context is not very common in public and formal dialogues in India (perhaps due to being stigmatized as “poor English”), it is quite prevalent in private and informal ones. %0a%3c %0a%3c Source: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/309168570_Familiarity_comprehension_and_use_of_Indian_English_only_L1_Indian_English_speakers'_psycholinguistic_judgments_and_interview_responses%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: E:)%0a%3c (:Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
